John Locke in his discussion about the paradox of the basins tells us to place one hand in the basin of cold water and the other in a basin of hot water.  When we remove our hands and plunge them both into a basin of &quot;room Temperature water&quot; .. what are the messages that are perceived by each hand?  Only one person involved here... one central basin.. but two conflicting messages. The hand coming from the cold water will tell you that the central common basin is very warm..the other hand coming from the hot basin will tell you that the central basin is very cool.  Perhaps, what we perceive as veterans of combat has a lot to do with where we are coming from at the moment.<br><br>
How we are feeling has something to do with subliminal and surface stimulation.  If I am coming from hunger a can of Spam is a thing of beauty.. if one is not hungry, Spam is something to throw at Jehovah's witnesses to drive them from your porch. <br><br>
Ever take a big draw from a carton of spoiled milk before you realized it was rotten?  After the gagging and spitting were you able to seek a fresh carton of milk or did you scratch milk off your list of things to drink?  How did you look at milk after the bad incident?  How are you stimulated by milk, Now?  Good or bad...are you hypervigilent about putting a glass of milk to your lips.. have you forgotten the incident and are unaffected.. Do you even know what is happening in your head when you see &quot;milk.&quot;<br><br>
&quot;Tuwe miye he,&quot; is the Lakota equivalant of &quot;Who am I?&quot;<br><br>
Maybe we can learn more about ourselves.. if we can learn more about the things that turn our knobs and pull our triggers.  Certainly, Viet Nam was more than a chug a lug of rotten milk.. there is much there that offended our senses!<br><br>
Looking forward to a good discussion.<br><br>
Humming Eagle
